<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   More on Address </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0101115494 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 0751 GMT 1 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0101115494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [New Year's message by President Nursultan Nazarbayev; place </F>
and date not given; from the "Mir" broadcast -- recorded] 
  [Text] Despite the fact that people are experiencing the 
hardships of the transitional period, as we call it, and that 
these hardships still exist, well, as the saying goes, hope is 
always the last thing to die. So I would like all Commonwealth 
states to look to the future with optimism. Why? Because the 
people who belong to the former Soviet Union have experienced 
many hardships. 
  I should very much like 1994 to be, for all the peoples, a 
year of insight, the year of the realization that only unity, 
only the preservation of the friendship that did nevertheless, 
exist in the former Soviet Union between the peoples, and [the 
preservation] of the wisdom that has always existed in our 
peoples -- that is what will lead to prosperity. 
  Be that as it may, life moves on. Whatever happens, we are 
doing everything to improve people's lives in the future. So I 
urge wisdom, prudence, calm, respect by every person for the 
person next to him, respect by people for one another, and 
respect by states for one another. 
  Today ultimata have to be removed from the vocabulary. Today 
one must speak with the language of understanding, the language 
of cooperation, and the language of mutually beneficial trade. 
  I wish everyone happiness and health. I hope that in every 
family there is prosperity, and that 1994 brings every family at 
least some small joy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

