<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tajik Parliament Lifts Curfew in Dushanbe, Other Cities </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3112173393 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1630 GMT 31 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> LD3112173393 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tajikistan's Parliament has lifted the curfew in 
Dushanbe, Kurgan-Tyube, Kulyab, and Kalininabad as of midnight 
January 1 at citizens request because the situation in the 
cities has returned to normal. 
  The curfew and state of emergency were declared in the 
capital on January 6, 1993 and were imposed on Kurgan-tyube, 
Kulyab, and Kalininabad on March 30, 1993 to restore law and 
order, guarantee the citizens safety, confiscate weapons from 
illegal armed groups, curb pillage and other heinous crimes. 
  The curfew was in effect from midnight till dawn. 
  The state of emergency is still in force. 
  As Nikolay Majar, a senior interior ministry official, has 
told Interfax, not later than January 6, 1994, the state of 
emergency must be either lifted or prolonged since the decree on 
it is valid only for up to one year. 

</TEXT>

