<H3> <TI>   Expected To Sign Agreements </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0301132294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1307 GMT 3 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0301132294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Boris Zaitsev] </F>
  [Text] New Delhi January 3 TASS -- Uzbek President Islam 
Karimov is to arrive in Delhi on Monday afternoon for the 
beginning of a three-day official visit. The visit is expected 
to include the signing of six agreements which will determine 
the further development of Uzbek-Indian relations, in particular 
in the commercial and economic spheres. 
  Karimov is expected to hold talks with Indian Prime Minister 
Narasimha Rao which will touch upon a wide range of bilateral 
and international questions. The Uzbek leader is also scheduled 
to give a speech at a meeting of the Confederation of Indian 
Industry. 
  As the "NATIONAL HERALD", a paper known to be close to 
Indian 
government circles, pointed out, "Uzbekistan desires to 
cooperate with India in the industrial and trade sectors in 
order to stimulate its privatisation process and the transition 
to a free market economy". Therefore the Uzbek delegation 
includes the heads of recently privatised key enterprises in the 
Middle Asian republic, according to the paper. 
  In its turn, India is ready to offer wholehearted help to 
the 
friendly ex-Soviet republic during this difficult transitional 
period of economic restructuring, the "NATIONAL HERALD" declared. 

</TEXT>

