<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Compromise Proposals on Radar Station Possible </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0201172294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1531 GMT 2 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0201172294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Latvia intends to clearly formulate its proposals 
connected with the possibility of letting Russia maintain its 
radar station in Skrunda in the near future. Riga hopes that 
negotiations on this issue will continue, Foreign Minister 
Georgs Andrejevs told Interfax. 
  He deplored the circumstance that in 1993 Latvia and Russia 
did not succeed in reaching agreement on the main issue -- 
Russian troops withdrawal from Latvia. 
  However Russia's new initiatives aimed at stepping up the 
withdrawal of the remaining military units are a positive 
factor, the minister said. (Interfax's note: Russia proclaimed 
its willingness to withdraw its troops from Latvia before August 
31st, 1994, if it maintains control over the radar station in 
Skrunda for another six years). 
  Andrejevs also expressed concern about the circumstance that 
most Russians living in Latvia cast their ballots for Vladimir 
Zhirinovskiy's Liberal Democratic Party and for communists. "We 
have no illusions in regard to the sentiments of many Russians 
living in Latvia. Our practice shows that what motivates them 
is the desire to reverse the course of history and return to the 
recent past, not the striving for democracy," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

