<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Navy Official Views Ukrainian Moves on Black Sea Fleet </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM3012134193 Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA in Russian 30 Dec 
93 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PM3012134193 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Aleksandr Khokhlov report: "What Moscow Thinks About This"] </F>
  [Text] We asked Admiral Igor Kasatonov, first deputy 
commander in chief of the Russian Navy, to comment on the latest 
events concerning the Black Sea Fleet's property. 
  "Unfortunately, neither the strategy nor the tactics of the 
Ukrainian military leadership are changing. Russia is being 
systematically squeezed from the Black Sea region. Now Kiev has 
waited for the Ashgabat agreements to be adopted and `gone on 
the attack' on engineering establishments of the Black Sea Fleet. 
  "This action itself had no significance -- either militarily 
or politically. The installations would have been voluntarily 
transferred to Ukraine by the Black Sea Fleet in January 1994. 
Someone in the Ukrainian military evidently wanted to assert 
his own personal importance and to prove his 'devotion' to the 
republic's political leadership. 
  "Russian sailors have no intention of `taking' their 
installations back from the Ukrainian military. Let them use 
them. But I believe that these will `count against' Ukraine 
when the new documents on the Black Sea Fleet are signed." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

