<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   10th Round of Fishing Talks Held With Japan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3012155293 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1344 GMT 30 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> LD3012155293 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Russian-Japanese fishing committee has discussed 
fishing in the economic zones of the two countries and fishing 
quotas. The 10th session of the committee was held in Moscow 
between December 16 and 29. 
  The Russian side, led by deputy chairman of the State 
Committee for Fishing Aleksandr Rodin and the director of 
Dalryba company Yuriy Moskaltsev were dissatisfied with fishing 
in Japan's zone because in the outgoing year Russia failed to 
catch the assigned quota. Among the causes of low efficiency 
they named the small size of areas given to Russia and the 
absence of steady fish resources there. 
  The two sides also exchanged information on the observation 
of fishing rules in 1993. Russian representatives said that the 
number of violations in the Russian 200 mile zone by Japanese 
fishing boats remains considerable: 59 in 1992 and 77 in the 
first 11 months of 1993. 
  The Japanese side promised to take tough measures to prevent 
the violation of fishing rules. 
  The two sides agreed to hold the next session of the 
commission in Japan in November 1994. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

