<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gives Year-End Interview </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3012220393 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1645 
GMT 30 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> LD3012220393 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Ukrinform correspondents Viktor Demidenko and Aleksandr </F>
Litvinov for TASS] 
  [Text] Kiev, 30 Dec -- In an interview with Ukrinform and 
Gosteleradio correspondents, Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk 
described 1993 as the year in which Ukraine began a transition 
to new forms of economic life. 
  Although there were many mistakes and miscalculations, he 
admitted, "Ukraine has not slid into the abyss, as some would 
have us believe." The fall in national income was 5 percent 
less than last year, and the decline in manufacturing slowed 
down. The country's industry produced a greater quantity of 
electric locomotives, special-purpose cisterns, power equipment, 
generators, wood working machines, and other goods. Farmers 
also had a good year, gathering 45.6 million quintals per 
hectare, considerably more than in 1992. The milk yield also 
increased. 
  Leonid Kravchuk described an agreement on prices and volumes 
of fuel deliveries to Ukraine signed with Russia and 
Turkmenistan as a positive step in the right direction. 
  In the interview he paid a considerable attention to the 
upcoming elections of people's deputies. The president 
expressed confidence that people would be able to come grips 
with the situation and, bearing in mind the pre-election 
campaign in Russia, would elect truly worthy and experienced 
politicians. 
  Taking about the most pressing tasks for the upcoming year, 
Leonid Kravchuk expressed confidence that Ukraine would be able 
to meet its targets for nuclear disarmament and to resolve the 
problem of the Black Sea Fleet in a civilized manner with 
Russia. The main thing for us, the president stressed, is "that 
there should be peace, tranquility, and confidence in the future 
in this common home of ours which we call Earth." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

