<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Urges Executive Branch To Cooperate With Parliament </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3012195693 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1907 GMT 30 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> LD3012195693 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russian President Yeltsin has called on staff 
members of the presidential structures to develop constructive 
cooperation with the new parliament. 
  The new parliament is more clever, more intellectual, and 
more politically competent than the previous body of Soviet 
power, Yeltsin said at a meeting with leaders of departments of 
the presidential administration that took place in the Kremlin 
Thursday [30 December]. 
  The year was difficult, he said, but the country has had for 
the first time free elections and has a democratic Constitution. 
  An Interfax correspondent reports that the president has 
stressed the need to improve the analytical work of the 
presidential apparatus. 
  Emphasis should be put on the quality, not quantity, of 
materials prepared by experts, he said. 
  The president has spoken out in favor of a reduced 
presidential apparatus. At the stage of discussions, he said 
all presidential staff members should advance proposals for 
decision-making, but once a decision is made, they should all be 
in agreement. 

</TEXT>

