<H3> <TI>   Shakhray on Parliamentary Party Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3112143993 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1327 GMT 31 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> LD3112143993 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Leader of the Russian Unity and Concord Party Sergey 
Shakhray, MP, said in an interview with Interfax Friday [31 
December] that the consultations between the leaders of the four 
largest parliamentary parties, Liberal Democrats, Russia's 
Choice, Communists and Agrarians, were "an unprincipled deal." 
  In his view, because only 50 percent of the Russian MPs were 
elected on party lists while the others, in electoral districts, 
these talks infringe on the rights of deputies who are not 
members of the four parties. 
  He thinks that reduction of the government headquarters 
might 
"weaken" the government in which he is a vice premier and step 
up the confrontation between the executive and legislative 
branches. 
  He did not rule out the possibility that he, Aleksandr 
Shokhin and some others would not be included in the new 
government. 

</TEXT>

