<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Election Aftermath </F>
<H3> <TI>   LDPR Favors General Amnesty for Any Convicted Coup Plotters </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3112174393 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1631 GMT 31 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> LD3112174393 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] As the State Duma goes into its first session on 
January 11, the Liberal Democrats intend to press for general 
amnesty to any one sentenced on political or economic charges 
starting from April 15, 1985, LDP [Liberal Democratic Party of 
Russia] leaders said in Moscow on Friday [31 December]. 
  The LDP which won over 20 percent of the vote in this 
month's 
elections, more than any other party, will hold 60 seats in the 
new Russian parliament. 
  The LDP proposes that the trial over members of the 1991 
coup 
attempt be ceased and criminal charges lifted against anyone 
taking part in this October's events including the siege and 
defence of the White House and other facilities. 
  It also wants leaders of the parliamentary revolt, now at 
Moscow's Lefortovo prison, to be placed under house arrest with 
some of them barred from any political activity for a period of 
three years. 
  The measure must be seen as a step on the way to public 
unity, the LDP statement says. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

