<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Media Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3012221193 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1700 GMT 30 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> LD3012221193 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondent V. Skvortsov including recorded remarks by </F>
V. Kucher, editor in chief of ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI; from the 
"Vesti" newscast] 
  [Text] [Skvortsov] Without waiting for New Year's eve, when 
the old and unnecessary are thrown away, our fellow journalists 
at the newspaper ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI have freed themselves from 
the intrusive stewardship of their masters, the Council of 
Ministers. 
  [Kucher] I will be honest about this. We have taken 
advantage of an edict by President Boris Yeltsin about 
reorganizing the government, and which has brought us an 
unexpected New Year's present. According to Clause 4 of Article 
18 of the Law on the Press, if a founder is reorganized, then 
all rights are transferred to its successor at the newspaper, 
which is the work force. 
  We held a meeting of journalists yesterday, and we became 
founders of the newspaper. We are profoundly convinced that if 
Russia is becoming a truly democratic state, then there should 
be no newspapers speaking in the name of the state or newspapers 
working under the diktat of any state authorities. Newspapers 
should perform another vital function: Supervision of the 
authorities by society. 
  [Skvortsov] They plan to solve the problem of finance 
themselves, with only part coming from the state budget. 
  [Kucher] We were not building up a newspaper business. We 
felt like a castrated tom cat in the hands of a rich boss. 
  [Skvortsov] We will find out the government's reaction to 
this breakaway next year. 

</TEXT>

