<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Finance Minister Fedorov Views '93 Economic Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0201091094 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 0800 GMT 
2 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0201091094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In the opinion of Russian Finance Minister Boris 
Fedorov, the government succeeded in pursuing a consistent 
financial policy in 1993. In an interview with the Russian 
media, he announced that over the last year prices had gone up 
nine-fold. Let me remind you, in 1992 they went up by 26 times. 
Moreover, they are quickly approaching world prices at present 
and this means the end of prosperity for low-effective 
enterprises. Boris Fedorov noted as a positive element the fact 
that it proved possible in 1993 to stop a flow of unjustified 
subsidies and credits to CIS countries. At the same time, the 
interest rates were considerably increased and privileges for 
non-effective enterprises reduced. This has led to an improved 
protection of the savings of the population and enterprises 
against inflation. 

</TEXT>

