<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Second Stage' of Reform To Reduce Army to 100,000 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0301193794 Minsk Radio Minsk Network in Belarusian 1815 
GMT 3 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS0301193794 </F>
<F P=104>  Minsk Radio Minsk Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Belarusian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A BELINFORM correspondent has been told at the 
Defense Ministry press center that the second stage of reform in 
the Belarusian Armed Forces will be carried out in 1994. There 
will be further reductions in the personnel of the former 
Belarusian Military District, which had numbered 250,000 troops 
at the beginning of the reform process. Supporting such a force 
was beyond the capabilities of the Republic's budget. In 
addition, the country's new military doctrine stipulates the 
forming of a nonnuclear force sufficient to protect the national 
sovereignty of Belarus. By the end of 1994, troop strength in 
the Belarusian Army will have fallen to 100,000. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

