<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Akayev Gives New Year's Address </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3112160093 Moscow Mayak Radio Network in Russian 1430 GMT 
31 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> LD3112160093 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Mayak Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [New Year's address by Askar Akayev; place and date not </F>
given -- recorded] 
  [Text] The most important and pleasing fact for me in 1993 
was the fact that our Commonwealth, the CIS, turned from an 
amorphous formation into an effectively operating mechanism of 
multilateral economic cooperation, on the one hand, and, on the 
other hand, into a mechanism of maintaining peace and stability 
and preventing conflicts on the whole enormous Eurasian 
continent. 
  Hence, my main wish to all of us is that in 1994 the 
mechanism should begin working in full and we should begin to 
overcome a political, economic, and spiritual crisis that all of 
us are going through. The most important thing -- my sincere 
wish is that finally, there should be a reconciliation at places 
where blood is being shed and civil war is under way. I am 
saying this with pain in my heart. My sincere wish is that 
people should return to a peaceful life. 
  One more thing, I would particularly like to wish to the 
citizens of Russia that 1994 should be a year of peace, 
stability, and progress. 
  It is the destiny of world history that without great Russia 
there can be no harmony, peace, or stability not only on the 
Eurasian continent, but in the whole world. 
  I would like to address all of us, CIS countries citizens, 
as 
my compatriots since we all come from a single Fatherland. 
Compatriots: I would like to wish you peace, well-being, 
solidarity, and fraternity in 1994. Happy New Year! 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

