<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Media Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Wins `Man of 1993' Poll in Moscow </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0401101194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0802 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0401101194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By unidentified ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 4 TASS -- President Boris Yeltsin 
enjoyed 12 per cent popularity and was the first in the "man of 
1993" opinion poll conducted before new year by the Institute of 
Parliamentary Sociology among 1,000 Muscovites. 
  Yegor Gaydar, the architect of Russian reform, received only 
four per cent, while nationalist leader Vladimir Zhirinovskiy 
came third with three per cent popularity, according to the poll 
published by the "MOSKOVSKIY KOMSOMOLETS" daily on Tuesday. 
  U.S. President Bill Clinton and noted Russian economist 
Grigory Yavlinskiy enjoyed two per cent of popularity. 
  Former British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, famous 
cellist Mstislav Rostropovich, Deputy Prime Minister Sergey 
Shakhray and former Vice-President Aleksandr Rutskoy received 
close to one per cent. 
  Two women listed their husbands as the man of the year. 
  The poll showed there are fewer people dissatisfied with 
their life in Moscow than across Russia. In the Russian capital 
the figure was 59 per cent, while in the whole of Russia it is 
75 per cent. 
  55 per cent of Muscovites said 1993 was unsuccessful for 
them, while 42 said it was successful. 

</TEXT>

