<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Enterprises `Panicked' Over Banknote Rumor </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0401114494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1134 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0401114494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Albert Kochetkov] </F>
  [Text] Tbilisi January 4 TASS--Georgian commercial bodies 
are panicked by persistent rumours that 50,000-rouble banknotes 
of the Russian Central Bank will be shortly withdrawn from 
circulation in the republic. Shopkeepers refuse to accept or 
change them for other money. Smart dealers swap such banknotes 
for 20 per cent of the sum exchanged. 
  Local financial experts suggest two reasons for the panic. 
Firstly, it might have been caused by Moscow press reports that 
the Russian market is flooded by forged 50,000-rouble banknotes. 
Secondly, it could have been caused artificially by local shady 
businessmen, who waxed rich last summer by cheaply buying up 
1961-1992 Russian roubles, which were then being withdrawn from 
circulation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

