<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia To Remove All Nuclear Fuel by 30 Jun </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0301204794 Tallinn ETA NEWS RELEASE in English 1640 GMT 3 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS0301204794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn ETA NEWS RELEASE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Tallinn, January 3 -- Russia has promised to 
remove nuclear fuel from its former submarine training base at 
Paldiski, north west Estonia, by midsummer, an advisor to the 
Estonian Foreign Ministry and member of the Estonian delegation 
at Estonian-Russian inter-state negotiations told ETA. 
  "Under a plan submitted by the Russian counterpart, nuclear 
fuel should be removed from Paldiski by June 30 this year," Mark 
Sinisoo said. 
  Russia has thus far followed the timetable of dismantling 
nuclear equipment, Sinisoo added. At the end of last year, 
Russia sent equipment and materials for dismantling nuclear 
devices to Estonia and another wagon is due to arrive in January. 
  "Following removal of nuclear fuel, Paldiski does not need 
Russian military presence and the so-called military dismantling 
should be decided at Estonian-Russian negotiations," Sinisoo 
said while adding that Paldiski must be integrated into Estonia. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-54825 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov002_t_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-002 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Colonel Sent To Promote Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0301193894 Tallinn BNS in English 1320 GMT 3 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0301193894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] TALLINN, Jan 03, BNS - Maj. Gen. Aleksander 
Einseln, the commander of the Estonian Defense Forces, appointed 
Col. Raul Luks as the commandant of Paldiski. The commandant 
assumed his post as of Jan. 1. 
  The commandant's task is to promote the withdrawal of the 
Russian troops, nuclear reactors and the submarine training base 
from Paldiski and the Pakri peninsula. He must also see to the 
establishment of Estonian laws in the town whose population 
consists mainly of aliens and the Russian military. 
  The commandant's tasks include securing cooperation between 
Estonian defense forces, border guards and the police in 
Paldiski, and preventing the looting of vacated Russian military 
facilities. 
  Luks was the deputy chief of staff of the Estonian Defense 
Forces before his appointment to Paldiski. 
  The Russian 93rd naval training base and its two nuclear 
reactors still remain in Paldiski. About 500 soldiers and 
officers were stationed there at the end of last year. Russian 
naval depots and a supplies company are also stationed in 
Paldiski. 
  The North Infantry Company represents the Estonian Defense 
Forces in Paldiski. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

