<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opinion Poll Accords Brazauskas Highest Rating </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0301164994 Tallinn BNS in English 1025 GMT 3 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0301164994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Jan 03, BNS -- President Algirdas 
Brazauskas of Lithuania has been declared the Person of the Year 
in his country, on the basis of a recent opinion poll. 
  He won the highest popularity rating - 31 percent - in the 
poll, taken at the end of December by the Baltic Studies polling 
center at the request of the newspaper LIETUVOS RYTAS, the 
newspaper reported on Friday [31 December]. Second to him is 
Vytautas Landsbergis, leader of the right-wing parliamentary 
opposition and former head of state, whose rating is nine per 
cent. 
  According to the same poll, Lithuania's population regards 
the introduction of the permanent monetary unit, the litas, as 
the most important event of 1993 in Lithuania, 26 per cent 
having expressed that view. Twenty-two per cent said the main 
event of the year had been the final withdrawal of Russian 
troops, the rest attaching the greatest importance to the Pope's 
visit or the presidential election. 
  As far as events in the world go, 29 percent attached the 
greatest significance to the October events in Russia, six per 
cent to the war in the former Yugoslavia and four per cent to 
the parliamentary election in Russia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

