<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Lucoil Continues To Be Principal Partner </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0401105794 Tallinn BNS in English 2032 GMT 3 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0401105794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Jan 03, BNS - The Russian oil company 
Lucoil will continue to be the principal partner of the 
Mazeikiai oil refinery this year, said Gediminas Kiesus, 
Mazeikiai assistant director general. 
  Kiesus said the Russian company guarantees stabile oil 
supplies and steady work of the refinery, which is very 
important to Western partners and banks, who might consider 
giving preferential loans to Mazeikiai. 
  According to a contract between Lucoil and the Lithuanian 
refinery, Mazeikiai is supposed to refine 6 million tons of 
Russian oil this year. Lucoil supplied only half of the amount 
it promised for 1993. Kiesus said Mazeikiai will refine 6 
million tons of Russian oil this year if all transportation 
problems are successfully solved. 
  The refinery received 5.1 million tons of oil last year. 
Three million were supplied by Lucoil, 2 million came in from 
different commercial companies and 50,000 were purchased by the 
refinery itself. 
  In 1992, Mazeikiai refined a record low of 4.9 million tons. 
The refinery hopes to get 8 million tons in 1994, which is still 
4 million tons below its maximum annual refining capacity. 
  Kiesus said Mazeikiai intends to buy more oil itself -- some 
50,000-100,000 tons each month. The oil will hopefully be 
purchased for preferential loans from foreign banks and 
financial organizations, he said. Loans for the refinery are 
currently under negotiation between Lithuanian energy officials 
and some Western banks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

