<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Interior Ministry Appeals to Citizens To Fight Corruption </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0401102494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0155 
GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0401102494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By unidentified UKRINFORM correspondent for TASS] </F>
  [Text] Kiev, 4 Jan -- In an appeal to the citizens of 
Ukraine, the Interior Ministry of the republic has called for a 
decisive fight against corruption, speculation, bribery, and the 
squandering of national property to be carried out on a broad 
front with the help of the population. 
  Foodstuffs, industrial goods, and essential raw materials, 
the document stresses, are being taken out of the country in 
various ways. The existing transparent borders, the lack of 
respect for laws, and the desire of some enterprises, commercial 
organizations, and individual citizens to get rich in this way 
are to a certain extent helping to make the situation 
significantly more acute. A criminal group that was trying to 
take 30 metric tons of nickel into Poland worth a total of 
$113,000 dollars was recently discovered by employees of 
interior affairs bodies. 
  Over the last two years, more than 40,000 attempts to 
smuggle 
out of Ukraine goods worth 1 trillion karbovantsi have been 
foiled by the military. More than 5,000 metric tons of grain, 
almost 12,000 metric tons of sugar, more than 1,000 metric tons 
of vegetable oil, and 3,000 metric tons of non-ferrous and rare 
earth metals have been returned to the state. 
  In connection with this, the Supreme Council and government 
have recently adopted several legislative acts for stabilizing 
the economic situation in the republic and defending its 
consumer market. The interior affairs bodies are relying on the 
understanding and support of the population for implementing 
these measures. 
  Ukraine's Interior Ministry, the appeal stresses, along with 
the security bodies, border guards, and customs officials will 
do all they can in the future to make sure the border is firmly 
closed and to protect the consumer market in a reliable fashion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

