<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lvov Oblast Council Bans `Subversive' Communist Party </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0301205394 Kiev KIEVSKIYE VEDOMOSTI in Russian 28 Dec 93 p 
3 </F>

<F P=103> WS0301205394 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev KIEVSKIYE VEDOMOSTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Yuriy Kril: "A Specter of Communism, Which </F>
Haunted the Lvov Region for a Long Time, Has Been Dispersed by 
Authorities"] 
  [Text] A special resolution adopted by the Lvov Oblast 
Council has deemed as subversive the activities of the 
reconstituted and illegally registered Communist Party of 
Ukraine. The resolution imposes a ban on issuing permits for 
staging mass communist rallies, as well as granting communist 
organizations facilities and telephone lines for their 
activities. Communist publications must not be circulated. 
Communists must not act as official co-organizers of any 
undertakings. 
  Thus, communists are being ruled with a rod of iron. 
Although there is no information regarding any punishments for 
violating the ban, from now on communists can hardly be expected 
to hold open party meetings. They have no choice but to 
continue their activities underground. Had it not been for the 
Oblast Council attack of rage, communists could have been kept 
under the authorities' watchful eye. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-54868 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov002_f_94015" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-002 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Civil Congress Urges `Close' Union Within CIS Framework </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0301205294 Kiev KIEVSKIYE VEDOMOSTI in Russian 28 Dec 93 p 
3 </F>

<F P=103> WS0301205294 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev KIEVSKIYE VEDOMOSTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Extraordinary Congress of the Civil </F>
Congress Discusses Tasks, That Is, Preelection Platform"] 
  [Text] The Fourth Emergency Congress of the Ukrainian 
Civil Congress was held in Kharkov and attended by deputies 
representing 17 regions. Having discussed the organization's 
election platform, participants in the congress came to the 
conclusion that regional organizations should independently 
determine the strategy of their electoral campaign, in light of 
local conditions and following guidelines drafted by the forum. 
  The Civil Congress is a leftist-centrist organization ready 
to cooperate with political forces fighting against nationalist 
extremism and advocating Ukraine's equal membership in an 
economic union with other former republics of the USSR. The 
delegates adopted a political declaration urging the formation 
of a close economic, diplomatic, military, and humanitarian 
union on the basis of the CIS; a resolution on the religious 
situation in Ukraine, and a statement regarding celebrations of 
the 340th anniversary of Ukraine's unification with Russia on 8 
January 1994. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

