<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Signs Edict on Karelia Territories </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3112115893 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1140 
GMT 31 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> LD3112115893 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Zlobin] </F>
  [Text] Petrozavodsk, 31 Dec -- Karelian residents have been 
given a New Year present -- President Boris Yeltsin has signed 
an edict "concerning the classification of individual 
territories of the republic as belonging to rayons of the 
extreme north and areas enjoying the same status." The 
residents of the north have been waiting a long time for this 
decision and regard it as equitable compensation for the 
discomfort they experience living in inclement climatic 
conditions. 
  Now, in keeping with the edict, the residents of Karelia 
have 
been given the right to draw their pensions five years earlier 
than before. Apart from this, the northern allowances, payable 
over and above the local wages, have been considerably increased. 
  However, residents in some Karelian villages are still 
dissatisfied with what they see as this kind of levelling-down. 
In keeping with the presidential edict, the republic has been 
divided into two zones with slightly differing benefits. It 
transpires that Kostomuksha, in the north of this lakeland area, 
is on a par with the southern Sortavala, where the climate is 
much milder. 
  In their appeal to the Karelian Supreme Soviet deputies, 
Kostomuksha inhabitants demand that this inequality in benefits 
be removed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

