<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Foreign Minister Views Relations With Ukraine </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0301122994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1131 GMT 3 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0301122994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature by Dmitriy </F>
Voskoboynikov, Igor Porshnev, Vitaliy Trubetskoy and others] 
  [Text] In an interview with Interfax Deputy Foreign 
Minister Sergey Lavrov said he hoped that in 1994 problems in 
relations between Russia and Ukraine would be resolved, and that 
bilateral ties would develop on the basis of "friendliness and 
fraternity." 
  According to Lavrov, these problems, above all issues 
connected with the destiny of nuclear arms and the Black Sea 
Fleet, must not be dramatized. "We must not forget that a vast 
country with an enormous infrastructure disintegrated," he said. 
"As soon as the two major problems are resolved, onward 
movement will begin in all areas of relations between Russia and 
Ukraine." 
  Preconditions for resolving these problems were ensured when 
the Russian and Ukrainian Presidents Boris Yeltsin and Leonid 
Kravchuk met in Massandra. 
  According to Interfax's interviewee, there are not only 
"sore" but also "healthy spots" in the Russian-Ukrainian 
relationship. At their meeting in Odessa held at the end of 
last year Russia's Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev and his 
Ukrainian counterpart Anatoliy Zlenko agreed to cooperate in 
resolving problems connected with the further development of 
Eastern and Central Europe. "The Ukrainian side assured us that 
Kiev's initiatives on the ways to promote cooperation between 
local countries provide for Russia's participation, not 
exclusion," Lavrov said. 
  According to him, Russia is interested in cooperating with 
Ukraine and other CIS countries in international organizations. 
At the latest UN General Assembly session the 12 CIS states 
advanced, for the first time ever, joint initiatives concerning 
the ways to combat drug trafficking, terrorism and environmental 
pollution. "It is noteworthy that the resolution on monitoring 
environmental protection from space submitted by the CIS 
countries was adopted by consensus," Lavrov said. 
  Interfax's interviewee drew attention to the circumstance 
that participants at the Ashgabat summit held at the end of last 
year decided to jointly request the UN to grant the CIS the 
status of observer of the kind enjoyed by, say, the European 
Union or the Organization of African Unity. 
  As Lavrov said, this decision was taken unanimously. Ukraine 
alone stood aside. "Ukraine abstained. Kiev voiced doubts as 
to the CIS being an "organization." But this is a purely 
terminological dispute," Lavrov noted. "There should be no fears 
that the CIS is turning into some "supranational mechanism." 
From the point of view of international law the term 
"organization" does not reflect "supranationalism." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

