<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Diplomat Dismisses Comments by Lithuania's Landsbergis </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0301123694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1131 GMT 3 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0301123694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature by Dmitriy </F>
Voskoboynikov, Igor Porshnev, Vitaliy Trubetskoy and others] 
  [Text] Russia's Foreign Ministry is not inclined to "react 
in earnest" to the numerous declarations of the former chairman 
of Lithuania's parliament and now right-wing opposition leader, 
Vytautas Landsbergis. To argue with him is as pointless as with 
the Liberal Democratic Party leader, Vladimir Zhirinovskiy, said 
a high-ranking Russian diplomat dealing with Baltic problems in 
comments on recent statements by Landsbergis concerning 
relations with Russia. 
  Speaking at a recent news conference in Vilnius, Landsbergis 
criticized the present Lithuanian leadership for its "policy of 
rapprochement with the East." 
  According to Landsbergis, "the last few months fully 
revealed 
the aggressive nationalism of Russia, whose policy had been 
identical to that of Zhirinovskiy, who only speaks more openly." 
  "Such escapades by Landsbergis are no longer surprising," 
said the Russian diplomat. "They have become so biased and 
subjective, that they can hardly be taken seriously, even in 
Lithuania itself," he said. 
  According to the diplomat, Vilnius' current foreign policy 
is 
aimed only at normalizing relations with all countries, 
including Russia, and not at rapprochement with the East. From 
this point of view he noted "certain achievements gained by 
Lithuania's present leadership." "Neighboring countries should 
live in peace and cooperate on a mutually-beneficial basis. 
This is an axiom, and to dispute it is senseless," the diplomat 
said. 
  According to him, "what motivates Landsbergis is largely 
political jealousy, since Lithuania's current president, 
Algirdas Brazauskas, has managed to achieve in the 
foreign-policy area much of what the right-wing radicals failed 
to achieve during their stay in power." 

</TEXT>

