<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk `Likely' To Attend Russian-U.S. Summit 14 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0401135294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1137 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0401135294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk is likely to 
arrive in Moscow on January 14 to meet with U.S. President Bill 
Clinton and Russian President Boris Yeltsin. 
  According to a well-informed source, Bill Clinton had 
invited 
Leonid Kravchuk to attend the Russian-American summit. 
  On January 3, tripartite talks began in Washington between 
U.S., Russian, and Ukrainian delegations. The talks will 
continue until January 8. The participants are discussing 
details of an agreement specifying the main aspects of nuclear 
disarmament, which is likely to be signed on January 14. 
  In an interview with Interfax, Ukrainian Vice Premier 
Valeriy 
Shmarov, who is in charge of the military-industrial complex, 
expressed hope that "during the talks with the U.S. and Russia 
we shall pass over to initialing specific documents," above all 
the agreement to be signed by the three presidents. 
  He pointed out that this document would enumerate guarantees 
given to Ukraine and specify which material, technical, and 
economic assistance Ukraine will be provided with during nuclear 
disarmament. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-54892 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov003_e_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-003 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  5 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk-Clinton Meeting Uncertain </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0401164294 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 1459 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0401164294 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kiev -- White House Press Secretary Dee Dee Myers 
has announced that the U.S. President will begin his "European" 
tour on 9 January. Bill Clinton will take part in a conference 
of NATO member countries' heads of state and government and from 
11 to 12 January will visit Prague where he will hold 
negotiations with Polish, Hungarian, Slovak, and Czech leaders. 
At Boris Yeltsin's invitation, the American President will make 
a three-day official visit to Moscow to "consolidate the 
democratic partnership between the United States and Russia," it 
officially reported. To conclude his tour, Clinton will visit 
Minsk. 
  Ukraine will not be visited by the head of the White House. 
However, INTERFAX reported on 3 January that a visit by L. 
Kravchuk to Moscow for trilateral negotiations has not been 
ruled out and that the Ukrainian president has been invited to 
do so in a recent letter from Clinton. The president's 
international service has informed a UNIAN correspondent that 
Nursultan Nazarbayev will make an official visit to Ukraine 
during Clinton's stay in Moscow. As for the letter, there is, 
indeed, an invitation in it to a trilateral meeting, but in 
Washington rather than in Moscow. It is not certain, THE 
WASHINGTON POST on 3 January quoted a high-ranking 
representative of the administration as saying, that the 
American and Ukrainian presidents will meet in Moscow; experts 
think that this will depend on the results of the U.S.-Ukrainian 
nuclear talks with the participation of the Russian side, which 
started in Washington on 3 January. Ukraine is represented 
there by Vice Premier V. Shmarov and Deputy Foreign Minister B. 
Tarasyuk. 
  Viktor Stelmakh, press secretary to the Ukrainian president, 
informed a UNIAN correspondent on 4 January that he could 
neither confirm nor deny reports of a forthcoming meeting 
between Kravchuk and Clinton in Moscow, since "there has been no 
final decision yet." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

