<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Less UN Attention to Ukraine </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0401182494 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 1459 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0401182494 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kiev -- At a briefing for journalists in the Foreign 
Ministry on 4 January, Viktor Batyuk, the permanent 
representative of Ukraine to the United Nations, summed up the 
results of the work of the Ukrainian delegation at the 48th 
Session of the UN General Assembly. He emphasized that since 
the radical change in Ukraine's political tack in respect of 
nuclear weapons and the Black Sea Fleet at the meeting between 
the Ukrainian and Russian presidents in Massandra on 3 
September, "less attention has been paid" to Ukraine at the 
United Nations. Viktor Batyuk characterized mutual relations 
with Russia as "a pendulum situation" and stressed that the 
Russian mass media "are defaming Ukraine." 
  The Ukraine representative said that members of the 
Ukrainian 
delegation made over 50 speeches in the course of the session, 
Ukraine co-sponsored 39 resolutions and was re-elected for three 
years as a member of the Committee for Program and Coordination. 
In Viktor Batyuk's words, Ukraine spoke against allowing any 
country's claim to be granted peace-making powers in any given 
region and demanded that peace-making actions should be carried 
out in accordance with the CSCE Charter and the major UN 
documents. 
  Viktor Batyuk confirmed that he has been appointed Ukraine's 
ambassador to Canada and that he will leave for Ottawa at the 
end of this week. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

