<H3> <TI>   Plyusch, Zvyagilskiy Nominated for Future Parliament </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0401201594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1831 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0401201594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ukrainian Speaker Ivan Plyusch and acting Prime 
Minister Yefim Zvyagilskiy have been nominated for deputies of 
the future Ukrainian parliament. 
  Plyusch was registered as a candidate from constituency 
No.455 situated in the Chernigov region. The Central Election 
Commission told "Interfax-Ukraine" that the speaker was 
nominated by the workers of a food plant of the town of 
Borznyany. 
  Workers of the Zasyadko mine in the Donetsk nominated acting 
Prime Minister Yefim Zvyagilskiy as their deputy. Prior to his 
appointment mayor of Donetsk and then government member, he 
worked as the director of the mine. 
  According to the election law, parties and working groups 
are 
entitled to nominate their candidates to people's deputies. The 
contenders must canvass more than 300 votes of the electors 
residing in this constituency to be registered as a candidate 
for people's deputy. 
  The elections to the Supreme Soviet of Ukraine will be held 
on March 27 1994. 

</TEXT>

