<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fuel Reserves Fall to `Unprecedented Level' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0501111694 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 2020 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0501111694 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kiev, [no dateline as received] -- Vilen Semenyuk, 
minister of power engineering, stated on 4 January that as of 1 
January, reserves of fuel in Ukraine had fallen to an 
unprecedented level -- three million metric tons of coal and 150 
metric tons of fuel oil, which in fact is the emergency reserve. 
Although energy consumption declined by 7.8 percent in 1993 
compared with the previous year and even by 12.8 percent in 
industry, energy consumption by the population increased by 30 
percent. In addition, energy enterprises owe suppliers 4.1 
trillion karbovantsi. According to information from the State 
Committee for Atomic Energy, new nuclear fuel was not purchased 
in the second half of 1993 because of a shortage of funds and 
spent fuel was not transported to Russia. Available resources 
should be exhausted in six months time. 
  Plans of the Ukrainian power engineering sector for 1994 
include purchasing 26 billion cubic meters of gas, seven million 
metric tons of fuel oil and 32 metric metric tons of coal 
including 20 metric metric tons through direct agreements. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

