<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shushkevich Said To Approve of Joining Security Treaty </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0401140194 Minsk RID in Russian 1106 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0401140194 </F>
<F P=104>  Minsk RID </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A RID correspondent has received this sensational 
information from CIS Executive Secretary Ivan Korotchenya: On 
New Year's eve Belarusian Supreme Soviet Chairman Stanislav 
Shushkevich officially notified the CIS Executive Secretariat 
about Belarus joining the CIS collective security treaty, signed 
at the CIS heads of state conference in Tashkent on 15 May 1992. 
Thus, Stanislav Shushkevich made a difficult step, because he 
had categorically opposed joining the treaty. The official 
notification of the CIS Headquarters was probably prompted by 
statements made by CIS officials demanding that Belarus 
precisely determine its standpoint with regard to the collective 
security issue. With this step Stanislav Shushkevich removed 
the trump card of his opponents periodically pressing for his 
resignation from the post of Supreme Soviet chairman. 
  However, the speaker believes that the Belarusian 
legislature 
has a right to introduce amendments in the process of 
ratification, regulating both the use of the Belarusian Armed 
Forces on CIS territory and the CIS Armed Forces on the 
territory of Belarus. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

