<DOCNO> FBIS3-54910 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov003_g_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-003 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  5 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shushkevich Comments on CIS Developments in 1993 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0401165794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1442 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0401165794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Chairman of the Belarusian Supreme Soviet Stanislav 
Shushkevich believes that confirmation of the idea to create the 
CIS, thanks to which the "hard" variant of former Soviet 
republics' division was excluded, was the major outcome of 1993. 
  In his exclusive interview with INTERFAX he underlined that 
the joining of new members, Azerbaijan and Georgia, confirms 
this fact. 
  Shushkevich hopes that in 1994 politicians will pay major 
attention to the strategy "but not to tactical conveniences and 
raising of definite political groups in different countries." 
  "If we decide to build the Commonwealth and want that the 
Russian-speaking population be respected in all its states, as 
it is in Belarus, then let us behave adequately! Any protest 
against separate moves of several Russian politicians can grow 
into an anti-Russian policy," declared Shushkevich. 
  He believes that principles of economic relations and 
primarily issues related to fuel and energy deliveries from 
Russia are the most important issues which have not been 
resolved yet. 
  At the same time, Shushkevich emphasized that those "who 
accuse him of anti-Russian moods" are guided by poor instincts 
and not by sound sense." 
  The head of the parliament awaits a new democratic 
parliament 
and, perhaps, presidential elections in 1994. 

</TEXT>

