<F P=103> LD0401180694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: Reports by </F>
Diplomatic Correspondents Dmitriy Voskoboynikov, Igor Porshnev, 
Vitaliy Trubetskoy, and others] 
  [Text] Chairman of the Belarusian Supreme Soviet Stanislav 
Shushkevich believes that confirmation of the idea to create the 
CIS, thanks to which the "hard" option of former Soviet 
republics' division was excluded, was the major outcome of 1993. 
  In his exclusive interview with INTERFAX he underlined that 
the joining of new members, Azerbaijan and Georgia, confirms 
this fact. 
  Shushkevich hopes that in 1994 politicians will pay major 
attention to the strategy "but not to tactical conveniences and 
raising of definite political groups in different countries." 
  "If we decide to build the Commonwealth and want that the 
Russian-speaking population be respected in all its states, as 
it is in Belarus, then let us behave adequately! 
  Shushkevich emphasized that those "who accuse him of 
anti-Russian feelings" are guided by poor instincts and not by 
sound sense." 
  He also warned that "a protest against separate outbursts by 
separate or different Russian politicians could grow into 
anti-Russian policy." 

</TEXT>

