<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin Working at New Residence </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0401140394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1137 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0401140394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin Tuesday 
[4 January] has had the first official meeting at the 
government's new residence at Krasnopresnenskaya Embankment 
(former White House) with Bishop of Istra Arseny, vicar of the 
Holy Patriarch, as well as with members of the Moscow Eparchy 
Council. The Bishop has consecrated the building where the 
Russian government will work from now on. 
  The Premier will work in the study formerly occupied by the 
former Russian prime minister, Ivan Silayev, and then Boris 
Yeltsin. The recent occupant of the study was the former speaker 
of the Russian Parliament, Ruslan Khasbulatov. 
  The Bishop of Istra blessed the activities of the premier 
and 
the government. Chernomyrdin has handed over to him two icons 
and added that over one thousand icons would be handed over to 
the Russian Orthodox Church later. 
  Taking part in the ceremony was the first Vice-Premier Oleg 
Soskovets who, together with other government members, moved to 
the new study in the building at Krasnopresnenskaya Embankment. 
  A spokesman for the Council of Ministers has told Interfax 
that the new government residence has an office for President 
Yeltsin. 
  The building on the Krasnopresnenskaya Embankment will have 
previous telephone numbers for the government hot line. The 
telephone numbers for the cabinet members will change due to the 
building's being switched to a new automatic telephone network. 
At Staraya Square, the telephone numbers began with 206. Now 
the first three figures will be 205. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

