<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Electoral Commission Arranging Move </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0401172494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1543 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0401172494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 4 TASS -- The Central Electoral 
Commission is presently making arrangements for the upcoming 
move to the White House government building, the former 
parliamentary residence. 
  Although the election campaign is over, the Central 
Electoral 
Commission is going ahead with its work, election officials 
stressed at their meeting on Tuesday. The Commission is now 
preparing a report on the election financing and the use of 
funds by candidates and election blocs. Arrangements are being 
made for elections in Russia's six constituencies where the 
December 12 poll was declared invalid. 
  But the main task to be tackled by the Central Electoral 
Commission is related to the presidential decree on measures to 
improve Russia's electoral system, Commission Chairman Nikolay 
Ryabov stressed in an interview with TASS. This document 
providing for transformation of the commission for the 1993 
elections to the Federal Assembly into a standing Central 
Electoral Commission of the Russian Federation "does not allow 
us to relax", Ryabov noted. 
  While drafting a law on elections in coordination with the 
Justice Ministry, the Central Electoral Commission will take 
into consideration all remarks made by individual candidates and 
parties. It will also head a system of commissions to be set up 
for holding elections tol power bodies of all levels in Russia's 
regions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

