<H3> <TI>   1,000 Journalists To Be Accredited to New Parliament </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0401155994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1405 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0401155994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS Correspondent Lyudmila Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 4 TASS -- "About one thousand Russian 
and foreign journalists will be accredited at the new Russian 
parliament," ITAR-TASS Was told by head of the Federal 
Assembly's Press Centre Valentina Lantseva. 
  "Realising that the ardent desire of journalists to cover 
the 
work of our parliament reflects the Russian society's interest 
in its proceedings, we are doing our best to create proper 
conditions for the press," she stressed, adding that "this task 
is far from easy so far". 
  The duty of the Russian parliament's press service "is to 
provide journalists, in keeping with the press law, with all the 
information they need". "The Press Centre has been provided with 
several rooms within the building of the former Council of 
Mutual Economic Assistance, where the State Duma will be housed, 
including the smaller conference hall, which will be switched on 
to the television and radio relaying systems," Lantseva said. 
"However, these premises will hardly be sufficient, especially 
for the work of news services," she added. 
  "The question of whether or not meetings of the parliament 
will be shown on TV and broadcast across the country, as it was 
the case with the former Supreme Soviet, is to be decided by the 
MPs themselves," Lantseva noted. The Press Centre is drawing up 
proposals for contacts with the "Ostankino" TV company and the 
Russian Television. Today, the press service, which consists of 
less than ten officials, is preparing equipment and other 
facilities for the future Press Centre. Accreditation cards 
have been ordered and will soon be received in Moscow. The 
Press Centre plans to issue a reference book, listing parliament 
members with their photographs and other information, including 
political likings and number of children, similar to the 
reference manual used in the German Bundestag. 
  "The question of premises for journalists at the Council of 
the Federation, the upper chamber of the Russian parliament has 
not been settled yet," Lantseva said. She said it could be 
raised only after the press building is transferred to the upper 
chamber of the Federal Assembly. 

</TEXT>

