<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karelian Leader's Proposals for Federation Council </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0401164694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1442 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0401164694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The chairman of the Karelian Parliament and deputy 
to the Federal Assembly, Viktor Stepanov, has told INTERFAX that 
on January 9 or 10 he intends to initiate preliminary 
discussion, with part of his colleagues in the upper house, of 
his proposal not to elect the speaker of the Federation Council. 
  Stepanov has said he intends to propose at the first session 
of the Federation Council January 11 to elect instead an 
executive secretary, as well as three co-speakers, each from the 
republics, autonomies, territories and regions who would in 
turns chair the House sessions. Stepanov has said that such a 
structural framework will help to achieve real, not just 
declared, equality of all subjects of the Russian Federation. 
  Stepanov believes there is no such equality so far, because 
as distinct from the Russian republics, territories and regions 
do not have their own constitutions and their heads are still 
appointed by the president. 
  Stepanov said that as an MP he would like to abolish 
Unitarianism in the Russian Federation and provide genuine 
federalism, when the component parts in the state have equal 
rights as is the case in the United States, Switzerland, 
Germany, and some other countries. 

</TEXT>

