<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Federation Council Agenda Group Completes Work </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0401165694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1624 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0401165694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Oleg Velichko] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 4 TASS -- The working group set up to 
work out an agenda of the first session of the Federation 
Council has completed its work, Russian First Vice-Prime 
Minister Vladimir Shumeyko said. 
  In an interview with journalists on Tuesday, Shumeyko said 
that the group has worked out a draft agenda which includes five 
points, namely: the electoral procedure and election of the 
chairman of the Federation Council, the upper house of Russia's 
new parliament, and his deputies, the approval of the list of 
committees of the upper house and their formation, the 
procedural regulations and life-support system. 
  Shumeyko added that most disputes were caused by 
disagreement 
among the group members over what should be discussed first: 
the procedural regulations or the elections. 
  Shumeyko pointed out that under the constitution there 
should 
be no joint sessions of the State Duma, the lower house of the 
Federal Assembly, and the Federation Council. However, Russian 
President Boris Yeltsin is likely to address both houses after 
which they will adjourn to seat separately. 
  As for the candidate to the post of the chairman of the 
Federation Council, Shumeyko said "it is too early to speak 
about that, at least until electoral procedures are defined." 
  He confirmed that the first session of the upper house will 
be held in the building of the former House of the Russian Press 
at Pushkinskaya Street 26. "By all standards this building suits 
perfectly for normal work of the upper house. The president's 
order should be fulfilled unswervingly," he said. 

</TEXT>

