<H3> <TI>   Federal Assembly Apparatus Chief Cited on Duma Opening </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0501092994 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 5 Jan 94 
First Edition p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PM0501092994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Vladimir Yanchenkov: "Parliament Apparatus Ready </F>
for Work"] 
  [Text] That is what Vladimir Podoprigora, leader of the 
Russian Federal Assembly apparatus, stated on the eve of the 
opening of the first State Duma session. 
  In contrast to the apparatus of the former Russian Supreme 
Soviet, which numbered 1,350 people, he noted, the new 
parliament's apparatus will consist of 537 employees. Since the 
Russian Federal Assembly consists of two independent chambers 
(the Federation Council and the State Duma) there will 
correspondingly be two secretariats in the apparatus. 
  A workable nucleus has been formed. The first experience of 
work with the deputies' commissions created by the chambers has 
shown that the parliamentary apparatus workers can fully cope 
with the set tasks. 
  The testing which has been carried out on the staffers has 
confirmed their high level of professional training. That is 
understandable, for 90 percent of the apparatus workers are 
employees of the former Supreme Soviet. These people have 
resolved and are capable of resolving tasks of any complexity. 
What tasks will be set them, and by whom, is another question. 
  The main task of the Russian parliamentary apparatus is to 
ensure the effect work of the deputies, to supply them with the 
necessary information in an entirely complete and objective 
manner, and to promote the high-quality formulation of the 
decisions the deputies will make. And they must do everything 
to ensure that they exert no influence in any way on the nature 
of the decisions which are made or on their content. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

